schemic stroke is a devastating disease with the only -approved treatment being intravenous () thrombolytics administered within 3 h from the time the patient was last seen to be normal.[2] he  clot-retrieval system is also an -approved device that can be used by trained interventional neuroradiologists and neurosurgeons to aid stroke treatment; it can be used for up to 8 h after the patient was last seen normal.[27]
nenhanced  scan is the initial rapid study of choice and can help identify early signs of stroke and to rule out hemorrhage. t is also used to identify signs of a large early infarction and to identify patients with less than one-third middle cerebral artery () hypodensity. atients with signs of large early infarcts on the initial  scan may be at an increased risk of an adverse outcome, while those patients whose  scan shows hypodensity greater than one-third of the  territory have an increased risk of bleeding complications.[2β€“7] ith all ischemic strokes the hemorrhagic risk increases with time, and the sooner patients are treated the better is their chance of a good outcome.
tandardized stroke assessment scales are used throughout the world in order to quantify patients' initial clinical condition and to measure clinical improvements. elow is a description of the four most commonly used scales.
he ational nstitute of ealth troke cale () is a 42-point scale, with the score ranging from 0β€“42. t is based on the evaluation and recording of 11 specific details tested on the neurological examination.  low total composite score indicates a mild stroke, while a high score indicates a severe stroke. he initial  stroke score also has significant predictive value. atients with a  stroke score < 1 appear clinically normal. hose with a  score > 4 can be considered for treatment.
he arthel index is a 1β€“100 scoring system that assesses an individual's ability to care for himself/herself, for example, in feeding, toileting, and ambulation. cores > 95 represent patients who are completely independent.
he modified ankin scale is scored on a scale from 0β€“5; zero indicates no disability and 5 severe disability.
he lasgow outcome scale is scored on a scale from 1β€“5, with 1 representing good recovery and 5 representing death.
he original landmark study on the use of tissue plasminogen activator (, specifically alteplase) for ischemic stroke that was published in the he ew ngland ournal of edicine in 1995 by he ational nstitute of eurological isorders and troke () rt- study group[2β€“7] demonstrated that there was no immediate improvement in patient outcomes. he results of -part  demonstrated good clinical outcomes at 3 months in 333 patients. here was an absolute increase of 11-13% for a favorable outcome in treated patients. he symptomatic intracerebral hemorrhage rate at 36 hours was 6.4% vs 0.6% in the placebo group. espite this increased risk of symptomatic intracranial bleeding 3-month mortality rates were similar in the treated (17%) and the placebo (21%) groups.
he magnitude of clinical improvement that was observed in the  trials and recently revalidated in the third uropean ooperative cute troke tudy, (-) and published in the  (eptember 25th 2008)[2β€“8] can only be appreciated by having a full understanding of the scoring systems. atients who met the following outcome scores that are used in the stroke studies mentioned appear clinically normal. he outcomes scores measured as a arthel index > 95, modified ankin scale < 1, lasgow outcome scale = 1, and  < 1 represent the clinical appearance of patients who have had a dramatic result with treatment despite facing a potentially life-threatening stroke.
he impressive outcomes can be translated into the clinical arena in the following manner: of patients who have sustained an ischemic stroke approximately one-third will stay the same, one-third will progress and die, and one-third will improve.
he use of  increases the likelihood of improvement from 30% to 40β€“50% and, despite the risk of hemorrhage being greater in treated patients, the mortality rates are similar in the treated and the untreated.[2β€“8] his may occur because perfusion to the area of the ischemic penumbra may be more important than the subsequent reperfusion injury, sometimes manifested as intracranial hemorrhage. t is important to explain this information to patients and their families in order to guide and assist them choose the treatment option.
he recent - trial results suggest that the window period for intravenous thrombolytics may be extended to 4.5 h after the onset of stroke symptoms. n all instances, having more time does not mean that we should waste it, because patients will have better outcomes if they are treated earlier. t has also been shown that community hospitals can also safely administer intravenous  if strict  protocols are followed.[35]
troke experts are now looking for reasons to treat patients with , instead of reasons not to treat. his represents a significant shift in the approach to the treatment of this potentially devastating and life-threatening condition,[2β€“9] which has often been ignored in the past due to the lack of treatment options.
ngioedema has become a well recognized but rare complication resulting from the administration of .[2] he reaction presents with oral and pharyngeal swelling along with tongue edema, similar to that seen in  inhibitor reactions. rompt recognition of this reaction is essential in order to prevent increased morbidity and mortality. irway protection, stopping the drug's administration, and treatment with antihistamines and steroids is advised.
he  clot-retrieval system is a mechanical embolectomy device. n the ulti- trial where the primary endpoint was recanalization of the target blood vessel, the device was effective 57% of the time. mong patients who experienced recanalization, there was a 2-fold survival advantage and a significantly higher proportion of patients lived without significant disability.[1036]
he trial did not show that thrombectomy actually improves stroke outcome. he 27% reduction in mortality that was observed between recanalizers and nonrecanalizers is evidence that the device works and, by allowing perfusion, seems to improve survival. any of the patients in the  trials had experienced significantly larger strokes than patients in the original   study and the treatment in some cases was extended up to 8 hours. urther outcome studies are needed to provide more conclusive evidence of the benefits of clot-removing devices.[36]
