Supratentorial intracerebral intraparenchymal hemorrhagic strokes are much less common than ischemic strokes, occurring in a frequency of about 20%; however, they are clearly the most lethal form of stroke and account for more than 50% of all stroke deaths[12β€“14] There is nothing more challenging in emergency medicine than receiving an obtunded patient in whom the CT scan reveals a large intracerebral intraparenchymal hemorrhage as shown Figure 1.
Figure 1Large intraparenchymal ICHIn this case it is important to stabilize the patient by securing the airway, carefully monitor the vital signs, and consider placing an emergency call to the neurosurgeon on call.[12β€“14] While the etiology of the bleeding is often mixed, it is essential to try and separate out the causes so that one can have a more comprehensive understanding of the management of these conditions in the clinical arena.
Understanding the neurosurgeon's approach to the evaluation and treatment of these patients will improve patient care. The large intracerebral intraparenchymal hemorrhage shown in Figure 1 occurred in the dominant hemisphere of an elderly patient with multiple medical problems and may not be a survivable insult even with optimal medical and surgical treatment.
